00:12:07,140 --> 00:12:09,140
Here's big mass for the nucleus,

274
00:12:09,140 --> 00:12:11,140
here's small mass for the electrons.

275
00:12:11,140 --> 00:12:14,140
And this is the sum over all the electrons.

276
00:12:14,140 --> 00:12:16,140
Sum over all the electrons.

277
00:12:16,140 --> 00:12:18,140
That's there, that's the kinetic energy.

278
00:12:18,140 --> 00:12:21,140
Then there's the forces between the electrons.

279
00:12:21,140 --> 00:12:25,140
That's plus E squared divided by,

280
00:12:25,140 --> 00:12:29,140
let's call it little r Ij.

281
00:12:29,140 --> 00:12:32,140
That's the distance between the ith and the jth electron.

282
00:12:32,140 --> 00:12:33,640
This is the coulomb

283
00:12:33,640 --> 00:12:35,140
energy between them, electrostatic energy.

284
00:12:35,140 --> 00:12:37,140
And what have I left out?

285
00:12:37,140 --> 00:12:40,640
Oh, I have left out the

286
00:12:40,640 --> 00:12:44,140
force between the protons and the electrons.

287
00:12:44,140 --> 00:12:46,140
So, that's one more term.

288
00:12:46,140 --> 00:12:50,140
I guess we can call it

289
00:12:50,140 --> 00:12:54,140
minus E squared because they're opposite charge.

290
00:12:54,140 --> 00:12:56,140
Attractive.

291
00:12:56,140 --> 00:12:58,640
Minus E squared divided by the distance

292
00:12:58,640 --> 00:13:01,140
between the ith electron and the jth electron.

293
00:13:02,140 --> 00:13:04,140
Either one of the nucleus.

294
00:13:04,140 --> 00:13:05,140
I don't know what to call it.

295
00:13:05,140 --> 00:13:12,140
Let's call it capital R one I.

296
00:13:12,140 --> 00:13:14,640
That means the distance between the

297
00:13:14,640 --> 00:13:17,140
first nucleus and the ith electron.

298
00:13:17,140 --> 00:13:21,140
And then another one for the second electron.

299
00:13:21,140 --> 00:13:26,140
R sub one, sorry, R two I.

300
00:13:26,140 --> 00:13:27,140
Alright.

301
00:13:27,140 --> 00:13:29,140
There are things which involve the electrons

302
00:13:29,140 --> 00:13:31,140
and there are things which involve the nucleus.

303
00:13:31,140 --> 00:13:37,140
So, here are all the things that involve the electrons.

304
00:13:37,140 --> 00:13:40,640
Now, intuitively, and I won't try to prove

305
00:13:40,640 --> 00:13:44,140
this, intuitively, there are two time scales here.

306
00:13:44,140 --> 00:13:47,640
One time scale is long and it has to

307
00:13:47,640 --> 00:13:51,140
do with the very slow motions of the nuclei.

308
00:13:51,140 --> 00:13:53,140
Why are the motions of the nuclei slow?

309
00:13:53,140 --> 00:13:57,140
Because the nuclei are very heavy.

310
00:13:57,140 --> 00:14:00,140
And they move around under modest forces, in fact.

311
00:14:00,140 --> 00:14:04,140
They're never accelerated very much inside a molecule.

312
00:14:04,140 --> 00:14:07,640
And so we think of them as very, very slow

313
00:14:07,640 --> 00:14:11,140
by comparison with the very, very rapid motions of the electrons.

314
00:14:11,140 --> 00:14:14,140
Electrons, much more rapid than the...

315
00:14:14,140 --> 00:14:17,140
So the electrons form a blur.

316
00:14:17,140 --> 00:14:19,140
And we're trying to get rid of

317
00:14:19,140 --> 00:14:21,140
that blur or replace it by something else.

318
00:14:21,140 --> 00:14:24,140
Well, this is fairly easy to do.

319
00:14:24,140 --> 00:14:26,140
In principle, in concept.

320
00:14:26,140 --> 00:14:29,140
To actually do it might be more difficult.

321
00:14:29,140 --> 00:14:32,140
But in concept, it's very simple.

322
00:14:32,140 --> 00:14:35,140
You take everything in the

323
00:14:35,140 --> 00:14:38,140
Hamiltonian here that involves the electrons,

324
00:14:38,140 --> 00:14:41,140
group it together, and think of it

325
00:14:41,140 --> 00:14:44,140
as the Hamiltonian of the electrons alone.

326
00:14:44,140 --> 00:14:48,140
But what about the positions of the nuclei?

327
00:14:48,140 --> 00:14:50,140
For present purposes now, we're going

328
00:14:50,140 --> 00:14:52,140
to say the nuclei move so slow,

329
00:14:52,140 --> 00:14:56,140
and the electrons adjust their wave function so rapidly,

330
00:14:56,140 --> 00:14:58,140
that in first approximation, we can say,

331
00:14:58,140 --> 00:15:01,140
the nuclei are not moving at all.

332
00:15:01,140 --> 00:15:05,140
They're fixed, they're nailed down, they're stationary,

333
00:15:05,140 --> 00:15:07,140
and we just fix them.

334
00:15:07,140 --> 00:15:08,640
And we think of this

335
00:15:08,640 --> 00:15:10,140
as a Hamiltonian for the electrons

336
00:15:10,140 --> 00:15:13,140
in a fixed background,

337
00:15:13,140 --> 00:15:16,640
the fixed background being

338
00:15:16,640 --> 00:15:20,140
the nailed down stationary nuclei.

339
00:15:20,140 --> 00:15:23,140
So we fix the positions of the nuclei.

340
00:15:23,140 --> 00:15:26,140
Once the positions of the nuclei are fixed,

341
00:15:26,140 --> 00:15:28,140
then this becomes the...

342
00:15:28,140 --> 00:15:31,140
the expression for the energy or for the Hamiltonian,

343
00:15:31,140 --> 00:15:33,140
but it's still a function

344
00:15:33,140 --> 00:15:35,140
of the position of the nuclei.

345
00:15:35,140 --> 00:15:37,140
It's a function of the position of

346
00:15:37,140 --> 00:15:39,140
the nuclei, but those can just be...

347
00:15:39,140 --> 00:15:41,140
You set the momentum to zero.

348
00:15:41,140 --> 00:15:43,140
Well, whose momentum?

349
00:15:43,140 --> 00:15:45,140
For the moment, yes.

350
00:15:45,140 --> 00:15:47,140
In fact, for the moment, we don't even need to...

351
00:15:47,140 --> 00:15:50,140
We just say they're nailed down, they're very, very heavy.

352
00:15:50,140 --> 00:15:52,140
Okay?

353
00:15:52,140 --> 00:15:53,640
We're not going to violate the

354
00:15:53,640 --> 00:15:55,140
uncertainty principle or anything like that,

355
00:15:55,140 --> 00:15:57,140
because eventually we're going to take those momenta

356
00:15:57,140 --> 00:15:59,140
back into account,

357
00:15:59,140 --> 00:16:02,140
and the approximation here is just that they move slowly.

358
00:16:02,140 --> 00:16:06,140
All right, then we take this Hamiltonian,

359
00:16:06,140 --> 00:16:08,140
which only involves the electron coordinates

360
00:16:08,140 --> 00:16:10,140
and the fixed positions of the...

361
00:16:10,140 --> 00:16:13,140
of the nuclei,

362
00:16:13,140 --> 00:16:14,140
and we solve it.

363
00:16:14,140 --> 00:16:15,140
What does that mean?

364
00:16:15,140 --> 00:16:17,140
We solve the Schrodinger equation,

365
00:16:17,140 --> 00:16:19,140
and we solve the Schrodinger

366
00:16:19,140 --> 00:16:21,140
equation for the lowest energy state.

367
00:16:21,140 --> 00:16:24,140
We find the lowest energy state,

368
00:16:24,140 --> 00:16:26,140
and in fact, more important,

369
00:16:26,140 --> 00:16:29,140
the lowest energy eigenvalue,

370
00:16:29,140 --> 00:16:31,140
the energy, the ground state energy,

371
00:16:31,140 --> 00:16:35,140
basically the ground state energy of the electrons

372
00:16:35,140 --> 00:16:38,140
in the background of the nuclei.

373
00:16:38,140 --> 00:16:39,140
Let's call that something.

374
00:16:39,140 --> 00:16:41,140
Let's call that...

375
00:16:41,140 --> 00:16:42,140
Let's see.

376
00:16:42,140 --> 00:16:44,140
Let's just call it E.

377
00:16:44,140 --> 00:16:48,140
E of electrons.

378
00:16:48,140 --> 00:16:52,140
All the terms that involve electrons.

379
00:16:52,140 --> 00:16:55,140
E of electrons.

380
00:16:55,140 --> 00:16:57,140
And what is it a function of?

381
00:16:57,140 --> 00:16:59,140
The only thing it's a function of

382
00:16:59,140 --> 00:17:01,140
is the positions of the nuclei.

383
00:17:01,140 --> 00:17:02,140
That's all.

384
00:17:02,140 --> 00:17:04,139
Everything else is taken care of.

385
00:17:04,139 --> 00:17:06,139
This is the lowest energy state,

386
00:17:06,139 --> 00:17:09,139
the lowest energy associated with

387
00:17:09,139 --> 00:17:15,139
the positions of R1 and R2.

388
00:17:15,139 --> 00:17:17,139
Those are the positions of the...

389
00:17:17,139 --> 00:17:18,139
of the...

390
00:17:18,139 --> 00:17:20,139
of the nuclei.

391
00:17:20,139 --> 00:17:22,139
Now what do we do next?

392
00:17:22,139 --> 00:17:24,139
Now we say, okay, let's take all of this

393
00:17:24,140 --> 00:17:26,140
and forget about it,

394
00:17:26,140 --> 00:17:28,140
erase it.

395
00:17:28,140 --> 00:17:29,140
We can't forget about it, of course,

396
00:17:29,140 --> 00:17:31,140
not completely.

397
00:17:31,140 --> 00:17:36,140
But we can replace it by

398
00:17:36,140 --> 00:17:38,140
the energy of the electrons

399
00:17:38,140 --> 00:17:41,140
as a function of R1 and R2.

400
00:17:41,140 --> 00:17:47,140
That's plus E of electrons

401
00:17:47,140 --> 00:17:51,140
of R1 and R2.

402
00:17:51,140 --> 00:17:52,140
What do we have now?

403
00:17:52,140 --> 00:17:54,140
Now we have a problem

404
00:17:54,140 --> 00:17:56,140
involving only the protons,

405
00:17:56,140 --> 00:17:58,140
or only the nuclei,

406
00:17:58,140 --> 00:18:00,140
excuse me, only the nuclei,

407
00:18:00,140 --> 00:18:02,140
a potential energy between them

408
00:18:02,140 --> 00:18:03,140
that was originally there,

409
00:18:03,140 --> 00:18:05,140
plus another term in the energy

410
00:18:05,140 --> 00:18:07,140
which also can be regarded

411
00:18:07,140 --> 00:18:08,140
as potential energy.

412
00:18:08,140 --> 00:18:10,140
It's a function of the position

413
00:18:10,140 --> 00:18:12,140
of the two nuclei,

414
00:18:12,140 --> 00:18:14,140
and therefore it's a contribution

415
00:18:14,140 --> 00:18:17,140
to the potential energy.

416
00:18:17,140 --> 00:18:19,140
This is the way that we eliminate

417
00:18:19,140 --> 00:18:21,140
out of the problem the electrons

418
00:18:21,140 --> 00:18:23,140
and replace it with something else.

419
00:18:23,140 --> 00:18:25,140
In fact, it's only a function

420
00:18:25,140 --> 00:18:27,140
of the distance between the electrons.

421
00:18:27,140 --> 00:18:29,140
And so what we actually find

422
00:18:29,140 --> 00:18:33,140
is that the entire dynamics

423
00:18:33,140 --> 00:18:37,140
of the electrons is summarized.

424
00:18:37,140 --> 00:18:39,140
We first of all have the Coulomb potential

425
00:18:39,140 --> 00:18:41,140
between the nuclei,

426
00:18:41,140 --> 00:18:42,140
but then another term

427
00:18:42,140 --> 00:18:43,140
in the potential energy,

428
00:18:43,140 --> 00:18:44,140
and the other term

429
00:18:44,140 --> 00:18:45,140
in the potential energy.

430
00:18:45,140 --> 00:18:47,140
When you combine it with this term here,

431
00:18:47,140 --> 00:18:51,140
it gives you a force,

432
00:18:51,140 --> 00:18:52,140
or gives you a potential energy,

433
00:18:52,140 --> 00:18:54,140
which looks something like this.

434
00:18:54,140 --> 00:18:58,140
When the nuclei are extremely close together,

435
00:18:58,140 --> 00:19:01,140
it's completely dominated by the Coulomb term here,

436
00:19:01,140 --> 00:19:02,140
repulsive,

437
00:19:02,140 --> 00:19:03,140
when they're far away,

438
00:19:03,140 --> 00:19:05,140
there isn't much energy between them,

439
00:19:05,140 --> 00:19:10,140
and in between there's some attraction,

440
00:19:10,140 --> 00:19:13,140
and that attraction is due to the electrons.

441
00:19:13,140 --> 00:19:15,140
However, we never have to think

442
00:19:15,140 --> 00:19:16,140
about the electrons again.

443
00:19:16,140 --> 00:19:19,140
For this hydrogen molecule,

444
00:19:19,140 --> 00:19:20,140
or whatever it is,

445
00:19:20,140 --> 00:19:22,140
we don't have to think about it.

446
00:19:22,140 --> 00:19:25,140
We just have an effective potential between them,

447
00:19:25,140 --> 00:19:28,140
and we solve the problem of two protons

448
00:19:28,140 --> 00:19:30,140
in a potential like that.

449
00:19:30,140 --> 00:19:31,140
We know what the solution's going to look like.

450
00:19:31,140 --> 00:19:32,140
It's going to sit at the bottom here.

451
00:19:32,140 --> 00:19:35,140
It's going to be some wave function.

452
00:19:35,140 --> 00:19:37,140
And that's a process of,

453
00:19:37,140 --> 00:19:40,140
number one, eliminating fast degrees of freedom,

454
00:19:40,140 --> 00:19:43,140
but we can also call it renormalization.

455
00:19:43,140 --> 00:19:45,140
We started with a potential

456
00:19:45,140 --> 00:19:46,140
which was just this potential.

457
00:19:46,140 --> 00:19:49,140
We got rid of the high frequency degrees of freedom,

458
00:19:49,140 --> 00:19:50,140
and the entire potential energy

459
00:19:50,140 --> 00:19:51,140
was then replaced

460
00:19:51,140 --> 00:19:54,140
by another function.

461
00:19:54,140 --> 00:19:57,140
So the potential was renormalized.

462
00:19:57,140 --> 00:19:58,140
That's the basic idea.

463
00:19:58,140 --> 00:20:01,140
All renormalization is associated with that idea.

464
00:20:01,140 --> 00:20:04,140
Eliminating very, very fast degrees of freedom,

465
00:20:04,140 --> 00:20:07,140
and replacing them by an effective,

466
00:20:07,140 --> 00:20:09,140
slow,

467
00:20:12,140 --> 00:20:15,140
renormalized Hamiltonian.

468
00:20:15,140 --> 00:20:19,140
Hamiltonian, or however you're doing your dynamics.

469
00:20:19,140 --> 00:20:20,140
Okay, so that's,

470
00:20:20,140 --> 00:20:22,140
that's renormalization.

