and so forth.

554
00:23:26,140 --> 00:23:30,140
So, let's keep that in mind,

555
00:23:30,140 --> 00:23:31,140
first of all.

556
00:23:31,140 --> 00:23:33,140
That's a bit of dimensional analysis.

557
00:23:33,140 --> 00:23:35,140
We have only units of length.

558
00:23:35,140 --> 00:23:36,140
Everything else is determined,

559
00:23:36,140 --> 00:23:39,140
or mass, depending on how we think of that.

560
00:23:39,140 --> 00:23:42,140
Okay, let's now talk about

561
00:23:42,140 --> 00:23:44,140
a typical quantum field theory,

562
00:23:44,140 --> 00:23:49,140
let's see, I think we'll start with

563
00:23:49,140 --> 00:23:51,140
a scalar quantum field theory,

564
00:23:51,140 --> 00:23:53,140
and I'll show you what's entailed

565
00:23:53,140 --> 00:23:55,140
in renormalization.

566
00:23:55,140 --> 00:23:58,140
We have, for simplicity now,

567
00:23:58,140 --> 00:24:00,140
just a quantum field theory with

568
00:24:00,140 --> 00:24:03,140
a single scalar field, phi,

569
00:24:03,140 --> 00:24:05,140
that's all there is.

570
00:24:05,140 --> 00:24:07,140
It has a Lagrangian,

571
00:24:07,140 --> 00:24:08,140
and from the Lagrangian,

572
00:24:08,140 --> 00:24:10,140
we derive Feynman diagrams.

573
00:24:10,140 --> 00:24:11,140
We're going to talk about those

574
00:24:11,140 --> 00:24:13,140
Feynman diagrams a little bit,

575
00:24:13,140 --> 00:24:18,140
and even set up roughly what a calculation

576
00:24:18,140 --> 00:24:20,140
of a Feynman diagram would look like,

577
00:24:20,140 --> 00:24:22,140
some simple ones.

578
00:24:25,140 --> 00:24:27,140
Okay, so there's a Lagrangian.

579
00:24:27,140 --> 00:24:30,140
Here is the Lagrangian for phi.

580
00:24:30,140 --> 00:24:32,140
It's very simple.

581
00:24:32,140 --> 00:24:35,140
It's just the derivative of phi

582
00:24:35,140 --> 00:24:38,140
with respect to either space or time squared.

583
00:24:38,140 --> 00:24:40,140
We've done these things before.

584
00:24:40,140 --> 00:24:42,140
That's the kinetic term in the Lagrangian.

585
00:24:42,140 --> 00:24:45,140
And then there may be a potential energy

586
00:24:45,140 --> 00:24:49,140
in the Lagrangian, minus V of phi,

587
00:24:49,140 --> 00:24:52,140
which is a function of phi.

588
00:24:52,140 --> 00:24:57,140
Now, what are the units of a Lagrangian?

589
00:24:57,140 --> 00:25:01,140
The units of a Lagrangian...

590
00:25:01,140 --> 00:25:03,140
Okay.

591
00:25:03,140 --> 00:25:06,140
What do we do with a Lagrangian?

592
00:25:06,140 --> 00:25:08,140
We integrate it over...

593
00:25:08,140 --> 00:25:10,140
We use a Lagrangian in the principle

594
00:25:10,140 --> 00:25:12,140
of least action.

595
00:25:12,140 --> 00:25:14,140
That's what a Lagrangian is for.

596
00:25:14,140 --> 00:25:15,140
It's whole...

597
00:25:15,140 --> 00:25:17,140
In classical physics, in any case.

598
00:25:17,140 --> 00:25:20,140
In quantum physics, it's used in the path integral.

599
00:25:20,140 --> 00:25:22,140
But basically, in either case,

600
00:25:22,140 --> 00:25:25,140
the quantity of real interest is the action itself.

601
00:25:25,140 --> 00:25:28,140
And what is the action in terms of the Lagrangian?

602
00:25:28,140 --> 00:25:33,140
It's the integral of the Lagrangian.

603
00:25:33,140 --> 00:25:36,140
But the integral of the Lagrangian over what?

604
00:25:36,140 --> 00:25:38,140
And space.

605
00:25:38,140 --> 00:25:39,140
Time and space.

606
00:25:39,140 --> 00:25:41,140
This is the Lagrangian of a field theory.

607
00:25:41,140 --> 00:25:43,140
So the interest in quantity,

608
00:25:43,140 --> 00:25:44,140
which is usually called S,

609
00:25:44,140 --> 00:25:45,140
sometimes S, sometimes action,

610
00:25:45,140 --> 00:25:47,140
sometimes I, it doesn't matter,

611
00:25:47,140 --> 00:25:49,140
but for now it's S for action.

612
00:25:49,140 --> 00:25:51,140
Huh?

613
00:25:55,140 --> 00:25:57,140
S for sex.

614
00:25:57,140 --> 00:25:59,140
That's like action, isn't it?

615
00:25:59,140 --> 00:26:01,140
No, no, no, I didn't say that.

616
00:26:01,140 --> 00:26:03,140
All right, S for action,

617
00:26:03,140 --> 00:26:09,140
and that's the integral d4x of the Lagrangian.

618
00:26:09,140 --> 00:26:12,140
And the action is always something...

619
00:26:12,140 --> 00:26:13,140
Yeah, question.

620
00:26:13,140 --> 00:26:17,140
Action has units of h-bar.

621
00:26:17,140 --> 00:26:19,140
But h-bar has been set equal to one.

622
00:26:19,140 --> 00:26:22,140
So h-bar is now dimensionless.

623
00:26:22,140 --> 00:26:24,140
Action is dimensionless.

624
00:26:24,140 --> 00:26:26,140
There's no dimensions at all.

625
00:26:26,140 --> 00:26:29,140
And that means whatever the Lagrangian is,

626
00:26:29,140 --> 00:26:33,140
it must have inverse length to the fourth power.

627
00:26:33,140 --> 00:26:36,140
The Lagrangian must have inverse length to the fourth power.

628
00:26:36,140 --> 00:26:38,140
The Lagrangian density in here.

629
00:26:38,140 --> 00:26:41,140
Must have inverse length to the fourth power.

630
00:26:41,140 --> 00:26:43,140
Now, what I'm really after

631
00:26:43,140 --> 00:26:46,140
is the dimensions of the field itself, phi.

632
00:26:46,140 --> 00:26:48,140
What is the dimension of phi itself?

633
00:26:48,140 --> 00:26:50,140
So let's see if we can figure it out.

634
00:26:50,140 --> 00:26:53,140
The Lagrangian has to be...

635
00:26:53,140 --> 00:26:54,140
Let's take this term here.

636
00:26:54,140 --> 00:26:57,140
This term here is derivative of phi

637
00:26:57,140 --> 00:27:01,140
with respect to x squared,

638
00:27:01,140 --> 00:27:05,140
and it has to have dimensions

639
00:27:05,140 --> 00:27:08,140
of inverse length to the fourth.

640
00:27:08,140 --> 00:27:10,140
Inverse length to the fourth,

641
00:27:10,140 --> 00:27:12,140
because it has to cancel this d4x here.

642
00:27:12,140 --> 00:27:15,140
d4x, or x has units of length.

643
00:27:15,140 --> 00:27:18,140
This must have units of length to the minus four.

644
00:27:18,140 --> 00:27:20,140
Okay?

645
00:27:20,140 --> 00:27:24,140
Well, whatever the units of phi are,

646
00:27:24,140 --> 00:27:26,140
the units of the derivative of phi

647
00:27:26,140 --> 00:27:29,140
are the units of phi

648
00:27:29,140 --> 00:27:32,140
times length to the minus one.

649
00:27:32,140 --> 00:27:35,140
That's the unit of the derivative of phi.

650
00:27:35,140 --> 00:27:37,140
Differentiating with respect to x just gives you a length.

651
00:27:38,140 --> 00:27:40,140
And that's the unit of length inverse.

652
00:27:40,140 --> 00:27:42,140
And now the square of this

653
00:27:42,140 --> 00:27:45,140
is just the dimension of phi squared

654
00:27:45,140 --> 00:27:47,140
times length to the minus two,

655
00:27:47,140 --> 00:27:48,640
and that has to give

656
00:27:48,640 --> 00:27:50,140
you length to the minus four.

657
00:27:50,140 --> 00:27:54,140
And that tells you that the units of phi squared

658
00:27:54,140 --> 00:27:58,140
must be length to the minus two.

659
00:27:58,140 --> 00:28:00,140
Or, to summarize,

660
00:28:00,140 --> 00:28:02,140
the units of a scalar field,

661
00:28:02,140 --> 00:28:05,140
the units of a scalar field

662
00:28:05,140 --> 00:28:07,140
are just inverse length,

663
00:28:07,140 --> 00:28:09,140
length to the minus one.

664
00:28:09,140 --> 00:28:10,140
Good thing to keep in mind.

665
00:28:10,140 --> 00:28:13,140
Very, very useful for all kinds of purposes.

666
00:28:13,140 --> 00:28:19,140
Um...

667
00:28:19,140 --> 00:28:23,140
That's an example of using some simple dimensional analysis.

668
00:28:23,140 --> 00:28:28,140
Now, what about the rules of Feynman graphs?

669
00:28:28,140 --> 00:28:29,640
Let's talk about the rules

670
00:28:29,640 --> 00:28:31,140
of Feynman graphs a little bit.

671
00:28:31,140 --> 00:28:33,140
First of all, the Feynman graphs

672
00:28:33,140 --> 00:28:35,140
all come from V of phi.

673
00:28:35,140 --> 00:28:37,140
V of phi might have things,

674
00:28:37,140 --> 00:28:38,140
like, in it.

675
00:28:38,140 --> 00:28:39,140
What does it have in it?

676
00:28:39,140 --> 00:28:41,640
V of phi has things in

677
00:28:41,640 --> 00:28:44,140
it like m squared over two.

678
00:28:44,140 --> 00:28:45,140
That's just a parameter.

679
00:28:45,140 --> 00:28:47,640
It really is, of course, secretly the square

680
00:28:47,640 --> 00:28:50,140
of the mass of the field divided by two,

681
00:28:50,140 --> 00:28:53,140
times phi squared.

682
00:28:53,140 --> 00:28:56,140
And then it can have things involving,

683
00:28:56,140 --> 00:29:02,140
let's call it g times phi cubed.

684
00:29:02,140 --> 00:29:03,640
And then it can have

685
00:29:03,640 --> 00:29:05,140
things with phi fourth in it.

686
00:29:05,140 --> 00:29:07,140
Let's call the coefficient of phi fourth lambda.

687
00:29:07,140 --> 00:29:12,140
That's a traditional notation.

688
00:29:12,140 --> 00:29:14,140
Lambda phi fourth, and on and on and on.

689
00:29:14,140 --> 00:29:18,140
It can have all kinds of terms in it.

690
00:29:18,140 --> 00:29:22,140
And notice that these terms also have dimensions.

691
00:29:22,140 --> 00:29:24,140
These terms also have dimensions.

692
00:29:24,140 --> 00:29:25,640
In fact, the phi squared has

693
00:29:25,640 --> 00:29:27,140
units of length to the minus two.

694
00:29:27,140 --> 00:29:29,140
Phi cubed has units of length to the minus three,

695
00:29:29,140 --> 00:29:31,140
and so forth and so on.

696
00:29:31,140 --> 00:29:33,140
And from that, we can read off

697
00:29:33,140 --> 00:29:37,140
what the dimensions of V of phi are.

698
00:29:37,140 --> 00:29:41,140
Okay.

699
00:29:41,140 --> 00:29:46,140
Now, let's talk about Feynman diagrams.

700
00:29:46,140 --> 00:29:49,140
Feynman diagrams are built out of vertices,

701
00:29:49,140 --> 00:29:52,140
and the vertices come from the potential here.

702
00:29:52,140 --> 00:29:55,140
Is g units of mass?

703
00:29:55,140 --> 00:29:57,140
G, let's see.

704
00:29:57,140 --> 00:30:02,140
So, yeah, g must have a unit of mass, yeah.

705
00:30:02,140 --> 00:30:03,140
Why is it mass?

706
00:30:03,140 --> 00:30:05,640
The whole thing has to have

707
00:30:05,640 --> 00:30:08,140
units of length to the minus four.

708
00:30:08,140 --> 00:30:11,140
All right, here's length to the minus three.

709
00:30:11,140 --> 00:30:13,140
This must be inverse length,

710
00:30:13,140 --> 00:30:15,140
but inverse length is the same as mass.

711
00:30:15,140 --> 00:30:16,140
Right.

712
00:30:16,140 --> 00:30:19,140
So, g would have units of mass.

713
00:30:19,140 --> 00:30:22,140
This obviously has units of mass squared.

714
00:30:22,140 --> 00:30:24,140
What about the dimensions of lambda?

715
00:30:24,140 --> 00:30:25,140
Dimension.

716
00:30:25,140 --> 00:30:27,140
Dimension less.

717
00:30:27,140 --> 00:30:28,140
No dimensions at all.

718
00:30:28,140 --> 00:30:30,140
That's significant.

719
00:30:30,140 --> 00:30:32,140
Dimensionless coupling constants are especially important

720
00:30:32,140 --> 00:30:36,140
in renormalization theory.

721
00:30:36,140 --> 00:30:39,140
The other ones have units of either mass, mass squared,

722
00:30:39,140 --> 00:30:42,140
and of course, if you introduce more terms up here,

723
00:30:42,140 --> 00:30:45,140
then you can follow what the dimensions are.

724
00:30:45,140 --> 00:30:49,140
Okay, now, a quantum field theory or the rules

725
00:30:49,140 --> 00:30:52,140
of Feynman diagrams are built out of two elements.

726
00:30:52,140 --> 00:30:54,140
One element are the vertices,

727
00:30:54,140 --> 00:30:59,140
and the vertices are read off from the potential here.

728
00:30:59,140 --> 00:31:01,140
For example, g phi cubed,

729
00:31:01,140 --> 00:31:06,140
represents a vertex in which three particles come together.

730
00:31:06,140 --> 00:31:08,640
And the coefficient of such a vertex

731
00:31:08,640 --> 00:31:11,140
in a Feynman diagram is just g.

732
00:31:11,140 --> 00:31:12,140
All right.

733
00:31:12,140 --> 00:31:16,140
Phi to the fourth, that's four particles coming together.

734
00:31:16,140 --> 00:31:18,140
This one has coefficient g.

735
00:31:18,140 --> 00:31:21,140
This one has coefficient lambda.

736
00:31:21,140 --> 00:31:23,140
What about m phi squared?

737
00:31:23,140 --> 00:31:25,140
Well, m phi squared is a very simple thing.

738
00:31:25,140 --> 00:31:26,640
A particle comes in, let's

739
00:31:26,640 --> 00:31:28,140
put a little cross to indicate,

740
00:31:28,140 --> 00:31:29,140
and goes back out.

741
00:31:29,140 --> 00:31:30,140
All right.

742
00:31:31,140 --> 00:31:34,140
Just, I put a little cross there

743
00:31:34,140 --> 00:31:37,140
just to indicate that something happened there.

744
00:31:37,140 --> 00:31:40,140
Namely, the particle was absorbed and re-emitted,

745
00:31:40,140 --> 00:31:44,140
and the coefficient is just m squared over two.

746
00:31:44,140 --> 00:31:46,140
So when you're building a Feynman diagram,

747
00:31:46,140 --> 00:31:49,140
a Feynman diagram has a value.

748
00:31:49,140 --> 00:31:51,140
The value corresponds to the

749
00:31:51,140 --> 00:31:53,140
amplitude for a process to happen.

750
00:31:53,140 --> 00:31:55,140
All right, it has a value.

751
00:31:55,140 --> 00:31:57,640
And in building it up, there's the

752
00:31:57,640 --> 00:32:00,140
elements of the vertices and the propagators.

753
00:32:00,140 --> 00:32:02,140
The propagators represent the motion

754
00:32:02,140 --> 00:32:04,140
from one point to another.

755
00:32:04,140 --> 00:32:07,140
All right, so let's talk about the propagators.

756
00:32:07,140 --> 00:32:12,140
The propagators, from one space-time point to another,

757
00:32:12,140 --> 00:32:15,140
we can just draw them as lines in between.

758
00:32:15,140 --> 00:32:16,140
Of course, the particle doesn't

759
00:32:16,140 --> 00:32:17,140
really move along a straight line.

760
00:32:17,140 --> 00:32:19,140
That's not the implication here.

761
00:32:19,140 --> 00:32:22,140
The particle is a quantum mechanical particle.

762
00:32:22,140 --> 00:32:25,140
But the motion from one point to another,

763
00:32:25,140 --> 00:32:27,140
or the emission from one point,

764
00:32:27,140 --> 00:32:29,140
the detection of another point,

765
00:32:29,140 --> 00:32:31,140
we'll call a propagator,

766
00:32:31,140 --> 00:32:32,640
and we'll just indicate it by a

767
00:32:32,640 --> 00:32:34,140
line going from one point to another.

768
00:32:34,140 --> 00:32:36,140
Now, I'm going to tell you

769
00:32:36,140 --> 00:32:38,140
what the meaning of the propagator is,

770
00:32:38,140 --> 00:32:40,140
the mathematical meaning of the propagator.

771
00:32:40,140 --> 00:32:43,140
The mathematical meaning of the propagator

772
00:32:43,140 --> 00:32:45,140
is just the amplitude that if

773
00:32:45,140 --> 00:32:47,140
you start a particle at one point,

774
00:32:47,140 --> 00:32:50,140
that if you create a particle at one point,

775
00:32:50,140 --> 00:32:53,140
that you detect it at another point.

776
00:32:53,140 --> 00:32:55,640
But mathematically, what it corresponds to

777
00:32:55,640 --> 00:32:58,140
is to starting with a vacuum,

778
00:32:59,140 --> 00:33:02,140
applying the field operator,

779
00:33:02,140 --> 00:33:06,140
phi at, let's call it, x,

780
00:33:06,140 --> 00:33:07,640
x, let's call this point x,

781
00:33:07,640 --> 00:33:09,140
and let's call this point y.

782
00:33:09,140 --> 00:33:10,640
These are not the x

783
00:33:10,640 --> 00:33:12,140
and y coordinates of a point.

784
00:33:12,140 --> 00:33:15,140
These are point x and point y.

785
00:33:15,140 --> 00:33:18,140
So you've created a particle at x,

786
00:33:18,140 --> 00:33:23,140
and now you want to remove the particle at y,

787
00:33:23,140 --> 00:33:26,140
so that might be some phi of y.

788
00:33:26,140 --> 00:33:28,140
The creation operator creates it,

789
00:33:29,140 --> 00:33:30,640
the creation operator that's in

790
00:33:30,640 --> 00:33:32,140
phi of x creates a particle,

791
00:33:32,140 --> 00:33:36,140
and you can think of it two ways.

792
00:33:36,140 --> 00:33:41,140
You can think of, let's think of it this way.

793
00:33:41,140 --> 00:33:45,140
The action of phi of y on the

794
00:33:45,140 --> 00:33:49,140
bra vector zero creates a particle at y.

795
00:33:49,140 --> 00:33:50,640
The action of phi of x

796
00:33:50,640 --> 00:33:52,140
here creates a particle at zero,

797
00:33:52,140 --> 00:33:55,140
but this can be read, create a particle at x,

798
00:33:55,140 --> 00:33:58,140
what's the amplitude that, after a certain amount of time,

799
00:33:58,140 --> 00:34:03,140
goes by that you find a particle at y?

800
00:34:03,140 --> 00:34:06,140
That's the meaning of this symbol here,

801
00:34:06,140 --> 00:34:10,139
the amplitude that if you created a particle at x,

802
00:34:10,139 --> 00:34:12,139
you would detect it at y.

803
00:34:12,139 --> 00:34:14,139
And that's what the propagator is.

804
00:34:14,139 --> 00:34:16,139
That is what the propagator is.

805
00:34:16,139 --> 00:34:17,639
It's just the amplitude that if

806
00:34:17,639 --> 00:34:19,139
you create a particle at x,

807
00:34:19,139 --> 00:34:21,139
you'll detect it at y.

808
00:34:21,139 --> 00:34:23,139
But now I can ask, what

809
00:34:23,139 --> 00:34:25,139
are the dimensions of this object here?

810
00:34:25,139 --> 00:34:27,139
What are the dimensions of this object?

811
00:34:28,139 --> 00:34:30,639
The vacuum, that's just a

812
00:34:30,639 --> 00:34:33,139
state, the state of lowest energy.

813
00:34:33,139 --> 00:34:36,139
Vacuums and states don't have dimensions.

814
00:34:36,139 --> 00:34:39,139
You wouldn't say the state has a certain mass.

815
00:34:39,139 --> 00:34:44,139
No, the state is just a specification of a configuration.

816
00:34:44,139 --> 00:34:48,139
It has no dimensions, but phi has dimensions.

817
00:34:48,139 --> 00:34:50,139
Phi has dimensions of inverse length.

818
00:34:50,139 --> 00:34:53,139
So what's the dimension of this object?

819
00:34:53,139 --> 00:34:56,139
Inverse length squared.

820
00:34:56,139 --> 00:34:58,140
Inverse length squared.

821
00:34:58,140 --> 00:35:01,140
Now, if there is no mass for phi,

822
00:35:01,140 --> 00:35:05,140
then there is no length scale in the problem,

823
00:35:05,140 --> 00:35:08,140
other than just the distance between x and y.

824
00:35:08,140 --> 00:35:11,140
x and y would be the only thing

825
00:35:11,140 --> 00:35:14,140
which would specify any length scale in the problem.

